{"answerArea":{"calculator":true,"chi2Table":false,"options":{"content":"","images":{},"widgets":{}},"periodicTable":false,"tTable":false,"type":"multiple","zTable":false},"hints":[{"content":"We just need to use a repeated version of the Pythagorean theorem to find out the hypotenuse lengths of each section of sidewalk. \n\nLet's start simply, with just the letters, before we jump into a bunch of calculations.  For the $\\green{1^{\\text{st}}\\,\\text{triangle's}}$ hypotenuse, we use the formula $a^2+b^2=c^2$.\n\n[[☃ image 1]]\n\nThis means that $c=\\green{\\sqrt{a^2+b^2}}$.","images":{"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/bc58d49f3b6d9d3e10d14025421659ea79096fb6":{"height":89,"width":400}},"widgets":{"image 1":{"alignment":"block","graded":true,"id":"image 1","options":{"alt":"□□□□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□ □□ □□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□ □□□ □□□□□ □□□□□. □□□ □□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□', □□□ □□□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□', □□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□ □□□□□□ □□□□ ('□'^□ + '□'^□). ","backgroundImage":{"height":89,"url":"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/bc58d49f3b6d9d3e10d14025421659ea79096fb6","width":400},"box":[400,89],"caption":"","labels":[],"range":[[0,10],[0,10]],"static":false,"title":""},"static":false,"type":"image","version":{"major":0,"minor":0}}}},{"content":"We remember that this hypotenuse becomes the base of the $\\pink{2^{\\text{nd}}\\,\\text{triangle}}$ .  Since the triangle height is still the same, let's keep using $b$ to represent it.\n\nSo we have:\n\n $\\qquad \\begin{align}\nd^2&=\\left(\\green{\\sqrt{a^2+b^2}}\\right)^2+b^2\\\\\n&=a^2+b^2+b^2\\\\\n&=a^2+2b^2\\\\\nd&=\\pink{\\sqrt{a^2+2b^2}}\n\\end{align}$\n\n[[☃ image 1]]\n\n","images":{"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/3c060708cad9a6d273145b9a1eb1521d8416ce3c":{"height":134,"width":400}},"widgets":{"image 1":{"alignment":"block","graded":true,"id":"image 1","options":{"alt":"□□□□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□□ □□□□ □□□ □□□□□ □□ □□□ □□□□□□□□. □□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□. □□□ □□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□', □□□ □□□ □□□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□'. □□□ □□□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□. □□□ □□□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□', □□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□ □□□□□□ □□□□ ('□'^□ + (□ □□□□□ '□'^□)). ","backgroundImage":{"height":134,"url":"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/3c060708cad9a6d273145b9a1eb1521d8416ce3c","width":400},"box":[400,134],"caption":"","labels":[],"range":[[0,10],[0,10]],"static":false,"title":""},"static":false,"type":"image","version":{"major":0,"minor":0}}}},{"content":"There's a pattern starting to form.  Let's try the $\\purple{3^{\\text{rd}}\\,\\text{triangle}}$ to see whether it continues.\n\n $\\qquad \\begin{align}\ne^2&=\\left(\\pink{\\sqrt{a^2+2b^2}}\\right)^2+b^2\\\\\n&=a^2+2b^2+b^2\\\\\n&=a^2+3b^2\\\\\ne&=\\purple{\\sqrt{a^2+3b^2}}\n\\end{align}$\n\n[[☃ image 1]]\n\n","images":{"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/64c919e467ea605b2a1a102f276d85c9533038a7":{"height":145,"width":400}},"widgets":{"image 1":{"alignment":"block","graded":true,"id":"image 1","options":{"alt":"□□□□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□□ □□□□ □□□ □□□□□ □□ □□□ □□□□□□□□. □□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□□ □□□ □□□□□ □□ □□□ □□□□ □□□ □□ □□ □□□ □□□□□ □□□□□. □□□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□. □□□ □□□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□', □□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□ □□□□□□ □□□□ ('□'^□ + (□ □□□□□ '□'^□)). ","backgroundImage":{"height":145,"url":"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/7d868e6541b0064081aa92c83ad795c8bc3b63e0","width":400},"box":[400,145],"caption":"","labels":[],"range":[[0,10],[0,10]],"static":false,"title":""},"static":false,"type":"image","version":{"major":0,"minor":0}}}},{"content":"Our pattern is that the length of the hypotenuse of the $\\blue{n^\\text{th}\\,\\text{triangle}}=\\blue{\\sqrt{a^2+nb^2}}$.\n\nWe need to know the length of the hypotenuse of the $\\red{18^\\text{th}\\,\\text{triangle}}$.\n\nFrom the pattern, this length is $\\sqrt{a^2 + 18b^2}$. In the pavement, $a = 3\\,\\text{m}$ and $b = 2\\,\\text{m}$, so:\n\n$\\qquad\\begin{align}\n\\red{\\ell}&=\\red{\\sqrt{3^2+18\\cdot 2^2}}\\\\\n&=\\red{\\sqrt{81}}\\\\\n&=\\red 9\n\\end{align}$\n\n[[☃ image 1]]\n\n","images":{"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/63f090bab280c566d6dfd107a894d4ceda3fc174":{"height":389,"width":400}},"widgets":{"image 1":{"alignment":"block","graded":true,"id":"image 1","options":{"alt":"□□□□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□ □□ □□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□□□ □□□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□. □□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□ □□□□□□□□□ □□□□□ □□□□□□□ □□□□ □□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□ □□: □□□□□, □□□□, □□□□□□, □□□, □□□□□, □□□□□□, □□□□. □□□ □□□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□'□ □□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□', □□□ □□□□ □□□□□□□□'□ □□□□□□□ □□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□'. □□□ □□□□□□□ □□□□□□□□'□ □□□□□□□□□□ □□ □□□□□□□ '□' = □□□□□□ □□□□ ('□'^□ + (□□ □□□□□ '□'^□)). ","backgroundImage":{"height":389,"url":"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/0a635ee2248346dd6181a4fe81121a2eccaff8c0","width":400},"box":[400,389],"caption":"","labels":[],"range":[[0,10],[0,10]],"static":false,"title":""},"static":false,"type":"image","version":{"major":0,"minor":0}}}},{"content":"The hypotenuse of the longest section of pavement is $9\\,\\text{m}$ long.","images":{},"widgets":{}}],"itemDataVersion":{"major":0,"minor":1},"question":{"content":"[[☃ image 1]]\n\nThe figure above shows the measurements for the pavement in a park meeting space.  The shortest section has a base of $3$ meters $(\\text{m})$. Each of the $18$ sections of pavement is a right triangle with a base equal to the length of the previous hypotenuse and a height of $2\\,\\text{m}$.  What is the length $\\ell$,  in meters, of the hypotenuse of the longest section?\n\n[[☃ radio 1]]\n\n[If needed, other perfect square measurements occur at the 4th and 10th sections.]:","images":{"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/a1935b7adf7a146380330aae16eb3a486ea8d0f3":{"height":356,"width":400}},"widgets":{"image 1